[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1.d4 d5 2.Nf3 Nf6 3.Bf4"]
[Black "Black vs. London: 2.Nf3 Nf6 3.Bf4 c5 Introduction"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Bf4
{ The London System. White secures the e5-square and hopes to safely develop his pieces and fight for a long-term initiative. White's usual setup is e3, Bd3, c3, Nbd2 with ideas of Ne5  (sometimes White delays kingside castling to play h4)  or O-O and e4. This approach can be especially annoying in the lines where Black plays ...e6 before ...Bf5, as White can fight for the initiative without risk because Black's light-squared bishop is passive and inside the pawn chain. However, Black has a strong and aggressive approach which takes advantage of the main drawbacks of the London System: White's delayal of c4 and weakening of the b2-pawn. }
3... c5
{ The most ambitious approach. Black strikes at the center in Queen's Gambit style, taking advantage of White's delayal of c4. If White had played c4 earlier, Black would usually have to play ...e6 to play a quick ...c5, which means locking his light-squared bishop inside the pawn chain. White would also have the possibility of pawn exchanges on d5 and c5, opening the position for his lead in development. However, Black doesn't have to worry about White taking on d5 and c5 because White hasn't played c4 yet, so Black strikes first. Black is fine with White capturing the c5-pawn because he can easily win it back with ...e6 and ...Bxc5 with a central pawn majority. If White doesn't take on c5, he will have to play e3 or c3 defending his central pawn, allowing Black to consolidate his queenside space advantage. Another idea Black has is ...Qb6, targeting the weakened b2-pawn. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1.d4 d5 2.Nf3 Nf6 3.Bf4"]
[Black "Black vs. London: 3.Bf4 c5 4.c4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Bf4 c5 4. c4
{ White increases the central tension. This favors Black because he can play ...cxd4 before White can play cxd5, taking over the initiative. ...cxd4 is dangerous because White hasn't supported his d4-pawn with another pawn. }
4... cxd4
{ Black has taken over the initiative.   5.cxd5  can be met with either  5...Nxd5  (taking advantage of the exposed Bf4)   or  5...Qxd5  (with a lead in development.)   5.Qxd4  Nc6  Black has a central pawn majority and White's queen is exposed.   5.Nxd4  admits that Black has a central pawn majority without White having sufficient compensation. Black can fight for the advantage with many moves , such as  5...Nc6  ,  5...e6  ,  5...Nbd7  , and  5...dxc4. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1.d4 d5 2.Nf3 Nf6 3.Bf4"]
[Black "Black vs. London: 3.Bf4 c5 4.Nc3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Bf4 c5 4. Nc3
{ Inaccurate. White fails to address Black's positional threat of ...cxd4, obtaining a central pawn majority.   More accurate would have been  4.e3  or  4.c3. }
4... cxd4
{ The standard response when White fails to support his d4-pawn with another pawn. Black is already fighting for the advantage due to his central pawn majority. }
5. Nxd4
{ White's center is unstable  (Black's pawns can chase White's pieces back)  but he hopes that Ndb5 will offer enough counterplay to compensate. }
5... Nbd7
{ Black threatens to play ...e5, which can only be prevented by Nf3. Since Ndb5 is no longer a possibility after Nf3, White doesn't have enough compensation for Black's pawn center.   5...Nc6  isn't as accurate as  5...Nbd7  because White can exchange on  c6  and  ...e5  is hard to achieve. After  5...Nbd7  , White is forced to lose a tempo with  6.Nf3  to avoid  ...e5. }
