[Black "Black vs. London: 3.Bf4 c5 4.Nc3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Bf4 c5 4. Nc3
{ Inaccurate. White fails to address Black's positional threat of ...cxd4, obtaining a central pawn majority.   More accurate would have been  4.e3  or  4.c3. }
4... cxd4
{ The standard response when White fails to support his d4-pawn with another pawn. Black is already fighting for the advantage due to his central pawn majority. }
5. Qxd4 Nc6
{ Black has the initiative due to his pawn center and White's exposed queen.   6.Qd1  is inaccurate because of  6...d4 !  and White can't play  7.Nb5  due to the  ...Qa5+  fork , but other queen retreats still leave White with a worse position as Black can rapidly develop  (...Bf5 or ...Bg4 followed by ...e6 and kingside development)  (where White has insufficient compensation for Black's central pawn majority.) }
