[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1.d4 d5 2.Nf3 Nf6 3.Bf4"]
[Black "Black vs. London: 3.Bf4 c5 4.dxc5 e6 5.e3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Bf4 c5 4. dxc5
{ White attempts to punish Black for an early ...c5 by taking the offered pawn. }
4... e6 5. e3
{ White isn't able to safely keep the extra pawn as  5.b4  runs into  5...a5. }
5... Bxc5
{ Black has at least equality due to his central pawn majority. To avoid being worse, White is likely to play c4 in the near future. After c4, Black has two strong options regarding the pawn structure.   1  Opting for a symmetrical structure with ...dxc4. In this structure, Black's main issue is his light-squared bishop, but he can actively develop it with ...a6, ...b5, and ...Bb7 with easy equality.   2  Keeping the tension by allowing cxd5 and ...exd5 where Black has an isolated d-pawn. This isolated pawn might be weak in the long run but also offers chances for an initiative due to the central space advantage   I prefer option two because it is more ambitious. Either way, Black is at least equal and can be confident entering the resulting middlegame. }
