[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1.d4 d5 2.Nf3 Nf6 3.Bf4"]
[Black "Black vs. London: 3.Bf4 c5 4.dxc5 e6 5.b4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Bf4 c5 4. dxc5
{ White attempts to punish Black for an early ...c5 by taking the offered pawn. }
4... e6 5. b4
{ White unsuccessfully tries to keep his extra pawn.   5.e3  is safer. } 5...
a5 { Undermining the pawn chain at its base. } 6. c3
{ 6.a3  doesn't safely defend the b-pawn because after  6...axb4  White's a-pawn is pinned; he can't take on  b4  without losing the a1-rook.   6.bxa5  Bxc5  favors Black who will soon take on  a5  with fewer pawn islands and a central pawn majority. }
6... axb4 7. cxb4 Nc6
{ Black will soon win his pawn back on the queenside. When he does, he will have a better position due to his lead in development and central pawn majority. The main ideas to know which win the pawn back are ...b6  (undermining)  , ...Ne4  (threatening ...Qf6 to increase the initiative, not giving White time to consolidate)  , and ...Nxb4  (a3 doesn't safely defend the b4-pawn because of the pin)  . }
8. Bd2
{ White defends his b4-pawn. Stockfish 10 considers 8. Bd2 to offer White the best surviving chances, although Black still has a huge  (possibly winning)  advantage.   8.a3  Nxb4   8.b5  Qa5+   8.Qb3  doesn't help because after  ...b6  White can't keep his pawn with  b5  because  ...Na5  hits  Qb3  , buying Black time to take on  c5.  Black also can  (and should)  favorably throw in  8...Ne4  before playing  ...b6.   8.Nc3  Nxb4  and  9.Nb5  can be met by either  9...Na6  or  9...Qa5  with a winning advantage due to Black's initiative and White's weak c5-pawn. }
8... Ne4
{ A thematic blow ! Black is now threatening ...Qf6  (winning material on c3 or a1)  as well as ...b6  (b5 can be met with ...Bxc5, winning the pawn back and threatening mate on f2)  . Black will win his material back while keeping the initiative. }
