[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1.d4 d5 2.Nf3 Nf6 3.Bf4"]
[Black "Black vs. London: 3.Bf4 c5 4.c3 Nc6 5.dxc5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Bf4 c5 4. c3
{ White protects his d4-pawn.   4.e3  is more accurate because it prepares to develop the kingside and sometimes White delays  c3  in favor of  Nbd2. }
4... Nc6 5. dxc5
{ White tries to keep the pawn, hoping that c3  (preparing b4)  is enough to consolidate. }
5... e6 6. b4
{ If White doesn't play this move, Black will win back the pawn with ...Bxc5 with a pleasant position. }
6... a5 { Attacking the base of the pawn chain. } 7. Nd4
{ White's most popular move. The idea is that White can meet ...axb4 with Nxc6 and after ...bxc6, Black no longer has ...b6 to challenge White's queenside pawn chain. }
7... axb4 8. Nxc6 bxc6 9. cxb4 Ng4
{ The key move ! White is up a pawn for now but is weak on the long diagonal. Black threatens to play ...Qf6 with a fork on Bf4 and Ra1. Black might also play for mate due to the weak f2-square. The advantage of ...Ng4 instead of ...Ne4 here is that Black might play ...e5.   This is especially relevant in the variation  10.e3  Qf6  and White can't play  11.Qd4  due to  ...e5. }
10. Qd4 { White controls the f6-square in an attempt to prevent ...Qf6. } 10...
e5
{ Black sacrifices a pawn for the bishop pair and to further expose White's queen.   10...Be7  is also favorable for Black but it allows White to avoid giving up the bishop pair with  11.Qb2.  To be fair White is more or less also getting crushed after  11...e5  and maybe  ...d4  , but I consider  10...e5  to be more ambitious and more in the spirit of the pawn sacrifice that Black has already made. }
11. Bxe5 Nxe5 12. Qxe5+ Be7
{ Black has fantastic compensation for the sacrificed pawns and plans to rapidly finish his development with ...O-O, ...Bf6  (White should prevent this from being a skewer, costing him more time)  , ...Bf5, likely advance in the center with ...d4  (and possibly ...d3)  , and centralize with ...Qd5. For a model game in this variation, see Adam Rakos vs. Istvan Taskovits. }
