[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Bf4 c5 4. e3
{ White's main response, protecting his d4-pawn. } 4... Nc6 5. c3
{ Although  5.c3  is the mainline , it is inaccurate.  5.Nbd2  is stronger. }
5... Qb6
{ Seizing the initiative ! Black threatens to take the b2-pawn. White can't afford to sac it because Black would be able to play ...Qxc3 afterward  (picking up a second pawn)  and return home with ...Qa5-d8. }
6. Qc2
{ I took a fresh look at this position since IM Yaacov Norowitz told me that the concession of ...g6  (the bishop would rather not be on the long diagonal)  gives White equal chances, and it turns out that Black has a dynamic alternative. }
6... Nh5
{ While 6...g6 is at least equal, Black can play for more using LeelaZero's recent discovery. }
7. Be5
{ Otherwise Black will win the bishop pair for insufficient compensation. }
7... f6 8. dxc5
{ White is forced to enter the following complications or else Black will be better due to his bishop pair and superior center. }
8... Qxc5 9. Bd4 Qa5 10. b4 { 10.Be2?  e5   10.e4?  dxe4  11.Qxe4  Bf5 } 10...
Qc7 11. c4 e5 12. cxd5 exd4 13. Nxd4 Bxb4+ 14. Kd1
{ Now Black has many options that give at least sufficient compensation for the sacrificed piece, Stockfish and LeelaZero believe Black is fighting for the advantage. All of Black's pieces will easily enter the attack and the White king is a long-term target. }
14... O-O
{ 14...Bg4+  ∞  15.Kc1  Qe5  16.dxc6  bxc6  17.Qxc6+  Kf7  18.Qc4+  Be6  19.Qxb4  Rab8  20.Qa3  Rhd8  21.Be2  Rxd4  22.Bxh5+  g6  23.exd4  Qxd4  24.Bd1  Rc8+  25.Bc2  Bf5  26.Qb3+  Kg7  27.Na3  Qxa1+  28.Qb1  Qd4  29.Qb7+  Kh6  30.Kb1  Qe5  31.Qxa7  Rb8+  32.Kc1  Qa1+  33.Kd2  Rd8+  34.Ke2  Re8+  35.Kf3  Qc3+  36.Kf4  Qe5+  37.Kf3  Qe2+  38.Kg3  Qg4#  Yaacov Norowitz 2412 - Alejandro Ramirez Alvarez 2568 , Reykjavik Open , Reykjavik ISL  (5.11)  (2018.03.10) }
15. dxc6 Kh8 16. Be2 Rd8
{ 16...Nf4!?  17.cxb7  Qxb7  18.Bf3  Qa6   18...Bg4!?  19.Bxa8  Bg4+  is unclear. }
17. Bxh5 Qe5 18. Bf3
{ 18.Be2  Bf5  19.Bd3  Bxd3  20.Qxd3  bxc6  =+ Black’s initiative continues. }
18... Rxd4+ { 18...bxc6!? } 19. exd4 Qxd4+ 20. Kc1 Qf4+ { 20...Qxa1?  21.Rd1 }
21. Kb2 Bf5
{ Black's initiative continues. The engines a series of only moves for White to hold on, but Black is the one fighting for a win and is probably objectively better. For example, }
22. cxb7 Rb8 23. Qc6 Qd4+ 24. Kb3 Bc5 { 24...Bf8!? } 25. Qb5 a6 26. Rd1 Qxd1+
27. Bxd1 axb5
{ 28.Bf3  Be6+  29.Kc2  Bd4  30.Nc3  b4  31.Re1  Bf5+  32.Ne4  Rxb7  is one way the game could continue. }
