8. Na3 { The most critical move, aiming to prevent ...b5. } 8... Bf5
{ Black wants to play ...e6 to challenge Na3  (by threatening ...Bxa3)  but that would lock his light-squared bishop inside the pawn chain. Therefore, he first develops his bishop outside the pawn chain, preparing to play ...e6. Black's light-squared bishop is strongest on f5 because if White plays Nb5 and meets ...Ra5 with a4, Black has the option of playing ...Bc2. Black also controls the b1-square, making ...Ra5-b5 stronger in some cases  (if White exchanges or moves Na3)  . }
9. Bc7 { Trying to win the b6-pawn. } 9... e6
{ Black has a powerful counter-threat: ...Bxa3. } 10. Nb5
{ 10.Bxb6  Bxa3  11.bxa3  Rxa3  White's  c3  and  a2  pawns are weak.   10.Nb1  can be met with the simple  10...b5  ,   although  10...Bxb1  11.Rxb1  Rxa2  12.Bxb6  Bd6  also gives Black a winning advantage. }
10... Ra5
{ Black has a queenside initiative. To win the b6-pawn, White must give up the a2-pawn, after which Black will still be better on the queenside  (space advantage, faster in the race to control the a-file, possibly ...b5-b4 in the long run)  .   11.a4  Bc2   11.Nd6+  Bxd6  12.Bxd6  Black has a lot of moves which give an advantage but the most accurate is  12...Ne4  and Black can soon target the b2-pawn with  ...Rb5. }
