1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Bf4 c5 4. e3
{ White's main response, protecting his d4-pawn. } 4... Nc6 5. c3
{ Although  5.c3  is the mainline , it is inaccurate.  5.Nbd2  is stronger. }
5... Qb6
{ Seizing the initiative ! Black threatens to take the b2-pawn. White can't afford to sac it because Black would be able to play ...Qxc3 afterward  (picking up a second pawn)  and return home with ...Qa5-d8. }
6. Qb3 c4
{ Gaining space and forcing White to make a decision regarding his queen. } 7.
Qxb6 axb6
{ Black has a better endgame because of his queenside space advantage and the open a-file. Black's doubled b-pawns are not a serious weakness because they aren't isolated, they even help increase Black's queenside initiative with the plan of ...b5-b4  (according to the principles 'attack a pawn chain at its base' and 'attack in the direction of your pawn chain/space advantage')  . }
8. Na3 { The most critical move, aiming to prevent ...b5. } 8... Bf5
{ Black wants to play ...e6 to challenge Na3  (by threatening ...Bxa3)  but that would lock his light-squared bishop inside the pawn chain. Therefore, he first develops his bishop outside the pawn chain, preparing to play ...e6. Black's light-squared bishop is strongest on f5 because if White plays Nb5 and meets ...Ra5 with a4, Black has the option of playing ...Bc2. Black also controls the b1-square, making ...Ra5-b5 stronger in some cases  (if White exchanges or moves Na3)  . }
9. Nh4 { White challenges Black's light-squared bishop. } 9... g6
{ The most accurate continuation. Black supports his bishop and prepares to play ...e6. Black has a better position due to his queenside initiative, White hasn't proven compensation. Black's intends to play ...e6  (threatening ...Bxa3)  and Nb5 can be met with ...Ra5 with the plan of ...Kd7 and ...Bd6. Black can double rooks on the a-file and/or use the g-file after Nxf5  (Black should recapture with the g-pawn)  .   9...Bd7  is the most popular continuation , but  10.Nf3  is somewhat annoying as it isn't clear that the bishop is better placed on  d7  than  c8  , especially since in the  Nb5  lines Black wants to be able to play  ...Kd7.   9...e6  is playable , but I'd rather be able to recapture with the g-pawn in order to obtain the g-file and secure control over the e4-square without weakening the e6-d5-c4 pawn chain. }
