[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1.d4 d5 2.Nf3 Nf6 3.Bf4"]
[Black "Black vs. London: 3.Bf4 c5 with 5.Nbd2 Bf5 6.c3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Bf4 c5 4. e3
{ White's main response, protecting his d4-pawn. } 4... Nc6 5. Nbd2
{ The most accurate move order, avoiding the 5.c3 Qb6 lines.   The idea is that  5...Qb6  can be met by  6.dxc5 !  where after  ...Qxb2  there is no pawn hanging on  c3  and White has the option of playing  c4. }
5... Bf5
{ Black aims to obtain a small advantage in an almost symmetrical position due to his queenside space advantage and more active queenside knight. Black intends to consolidate his c5-pawn with ...e6 next, so White should strike with dxc5 now if he wants to fight for the advantage. }
6. c3 Qb6
{ Black can play ...Qb6 now, as after ...Qxb2 Black is threatening to take on c3. }
7. Nh4
{ 7.Nh4 is the most critical move.   7.Qb3  c4!  and White must go for the inferior endgame after  8.Qxb6  axb6.   7.Qc1  is passive and Black has superior piece activity. The main move at master level is  7...Rc8  , creating an x-ray and threatening to take twice on  d4  , but  7...e6  and  7...h6  are also strong. }
7... Bd7
{ Black preserves his bishop pair. White still has to deal with the threat of ...Qxb2. }
8. Qb3
{ 8.Qc2?!  concedes the initiative without a fight. Black can fight for the bishop pair with  8...Nh5  with  ...Rc8  (threatening ...cxd4 followed by ...Nxd4)  (and rapid development coming.)   8.b3?  weakens the dark-squares without obtaining compensation. Black could have a better position with normal developing moves , but most energetic is  8...cxd4!  9.exd4   9.cxd4  Ne4!  with  ...e5  and  ...Bb4+  9...e5!  Black will meet  dxe5  with  ...Bc5  and  ...Ng4  with a decisive initiative.   8.Qc1?  cxd4  9.exd4  e5!  gives Black a decisive initiative. For example ,  10.dxe5  Ng4!  11.Bg3  Bc5!  and  f2  drops off. }
8... c4 9. Qc2
{ White hopes to have a good version of this structure because Black isn't able to play ...Bf5 to target White's queen.   8.Qxb6  axb6  is a better endgame for Black. }
9... Nh5
{ Black threatens to win the bishop pair with ...Nxf4. Black was able to save his bishop pair with ...Bd7, but White can't do the same. }
10. Bg3 Nxg3
{ Black wins the bishop pair. White will need to try to obtain counterplay with b3 soon, but that will help Black open the position for his bishop pair. }
11. hxg3 g5
{ The sharpest response, which happens to be a novelty. Black targets White's h4-knight and starts to fight for the initiative.   11...g6  is theory. Black has a small plus score. }
12. Nhf3 g4
{ This is a sharp position where both sides have chances. White is almost certainly going to be out of book at this point, as 11...g5 is a novelty. Black plans to rapidly develop  (...e6 or ...e5 with ...Be7)  and can castle either direction  (most likely queenside)  . Black is also likely to support his g4-pawn with ...h5. The onus is on White to find counterplay here, as Black has the bishop pair and a space advantage. Stockfish isn't sure what to make about this position, as it keeps changing its mind. However, at high depth  (30+)  , after following its suggestions for a few moves and letting it sit, Stockfish generally prefers Black by at least 1/5 of a pawn.   Black should probably meet  13.Ng1  with the sharp  13...e5  though  13...O-O-O  , and  13...h5  are also playable.   13.Nh4  can be met with  13...e6  , or  13...e5  , or  13...h5. }
*

