[White "1.d4 d5 2.Nf3 Nf6 3.Bf4"]
[Black "Black vs. London: 3.Bf4 c5 with 5.Nbd2 Bf5 6.dxc5 e6 7.Nd4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Bf4 c5 4. e3
{ White's main response, protecting his d4-pawn. } 4... Nc6 5. Nbd2
{ The most accurate move order, avoiding the 5.c3 Qb6 lines.   The idea is that  5...Qb6  can be met by  6.dxc5 !  where after  ...Qxb2  there is no pawn hanging on  c3  and White has the option of playing  c4. }
5... Bf5
{ Black aims to obtain a small advantage in an almost symmetrical position due to his queenside space advantage and more active queenside knight. Black intends to consolidate his c5-pawn with ...e6 next, so White must strike with dxc5 now if he wants to fight for the advantage. }
6. dxc5
{ Critical. White aims to exploit the loose bishop on f5 by meeting ...e6 with Nd4  (threatening to prevent ...b6 with Nxc6 followed by b4)  . }
6... e6 7. Nd4 Bxc5
{ Black wins his pawn back at the cost of the bishop pair. } 8. Nxf5 exf5
{ This is a dynamically balanced position where both sides have chances to play for a win. White has the bishop pair and fewer pawn islands. Black has more space and a lead in development. For a model game in this variation, see Son Nguyen vs. Mikhael Mchedlishvili.   9.Bd3  can be met by  9...g6  ,  9...Ne4  ,   or even the unclear  9...O-O  10.Bxf5  d4 !   9.Nf3  Ne4 !  followed by  ...g5  gives Black the initiative.   9.Be2  can be met with  9...d4  or  9...0-0  with at least equality.   9.Nb3  should be met by  9...Bb6!   9.c3 !  is the most critical but after  9...O-O  , Black's lead in development is becoming dangerously large , White has to be careful to avoid disaster. For example ,  10.Bd3 ?!  runs into  10...d4 !  where Black can recapture on  d4  with the bishop  (with a fork coming)  11.exd4  Bxd4  12.cxd4  Qxd4    13.Qf3  and play  13...Rfe8+  to prevent White from castling. Black will win his piece back with  ...Nd5-b4  and/or  ...Rad8  with a powerful initiative. }
