[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1.d4 d5 2.Bf4"]
[Black "Black vs. London: 2.Bf4 c5 3.e4 Nc6 4.Nc3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5
{ Similar to 2.Nf3 Nf6 3.Bf4 c5, Black strikes in the center, taking advantage of White's delayal of c4 and prepares to target White's b2-pawn with ...Qb6. }
3. e4
{ White sacrifices a pawn in an attempt to obtain the initiative.   The main idea is that after  3...dxe4  White has  4.d5  with a space advantage and easy development. }
3... Nc6 { Black declines the gambit, opting to focus on development. } 4. Nc3
{ White defends his e4-pawn and develops a piece. The consequence of this approach is that White fails to defend his d4-pawn. }
4... cxd4
{ Winning a pawn and attacking Nc3. White must play concretely to justify his sacrifice, as retreating his knight would allow ...dxe4 and ...e5. }
5. Nb5 { White threatens Nc7+. } 5... e5
{ Defending against Nc7+ and threatening White's bishop. } 6. exd5
{ Otherwise Black would be up a pawn with the initiative for free. } 6... exf4
{ 6...Qxd5  loses to  7.Nc7+.  Black has a better position due to his bishop pair and space advantage.   7.dxc6  can be met with  7...Bb4+   or  7...bxc6. }
*

