{ White defends his e4-pawn and develops a piece. The consequence of this approach is that White fails to defend his d4-pawn. }
4... cxd4
{ Winning a pawn and attacking Nc3. White must play concretely to justify his sacrifice, as retreating his knight would allow ...dxe4 and ...e5. }
5. exd5 dxc3 6. dxc6 Qxd1+ 7. Rxd1 bxc6
{ Black can easily finish his kingside development with ...e6, ...Nf6, ...Be7/...Bc5, and either ...O-O or ...Ke7. Black can meet Bc7 with ...Bd7  (or ...Bg4 followed by ...Bd7, trying to provoke f3)  or even just ...e6  (Black can later develop his light-squared bishop to b7 and free it with ...c5)  . Both sides have chances in this dynamically balanced endgame. }
