Qxd5
{ Black has a lead in development and White's center is falling apart, so White needs something concrete to justify his approach. }
5. Nc3
{ White sacrifices the d4-pawn, hoping for sufficient counterplay after Nd5. }
5... Qxd4 { Black grabs a pawn and threatens ...Qxf4. } 6. Nd5
{ White threatens Nc7+ and defends his bishop.   The complications  6.Be3  Qb4  favor Black. }
6... e5
{ Black sacrifices the exchange, knowing that he can later win his material back as White's knight will be trapped in the corner. }
7. Nc7+ Kd8 8. Nxa8 exf4
{ Black has excellent compensation for the exchange in the form of his space advantage, lead in development, bishop pair, extra pawn, and White's trapped a8-knight. Black will soon win back the knight with ...Bd7 followed by ...Kc8-b8-xa8 with at least equal chances. For a model game in this variation, see Alexander Velikanov vs. Conrad Holt.   The main line is  9.Nf3  Qxd1+  10.Rxd1+  Bd7  and White can't stop  ...Kc8-b8-xa8  , although before playing  ...Kb8  , Black should defend his d7-bishop with  ...Nf6  or move his light-squared bishop  (probably ...Be6, ...Bf5, or ...Bg4)  (.) }
