[White "1.d4 d5 2.Bf4"]
[Black "Black vs. London: 2.Bf4 c5 3.e3 Nc6 4.Nc3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5
{ Similar to 2.Nf3 Nf6 3.Bf4 c5, Black strikes in the center, taking advantage of White's delayal of c4 and prepares to target White's b2-pawn with ...Qb6. }
3. e3
{ Black was threatening to obtain a central pawn majority with 3...cxd4, so White supports his d4-pawn. }
3... Nc6 4. Nc3
{ White makes the tactical threat Nb5 at the cost of blocking his c-pawn. }
4... cxd4
{ Black makes sure that White can't play dxc5 before he prevents the Nb5 threat with ...a6.   4...a6  allows  5.dxc5  and Black can't immediately try to win back the pawn as the d5-pawn is hanging and the e4-break is stronger when White has already played  Nc3. }
5. exd4 a6
{ Black prevents Nb5. This is a relatively normal Carlsbad structure where Black is a slightly behind in development but Nc3 is misplaced  (White wants to be able to play c3)  . Black intends to develop rapidly  (...Nf6, ...Bf5 or ...Bg4, ...e6, ...Bd6, ...0-0, ...Rc8)  and attack on the queenside  (minority attack style with ...b5-b4, possibly supported by the queen and a-pawn)  .   It's worth mentioning that  6.Nf3  should be met with  6...Bg4!  because  6...Nc6  7.Ne5  e6  8.Nxc6  is rather dry and hard to play for a win. }
