1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5
{ Similar to 2.Nf3 Nf6 3.Bf4 c5, Black strikes in the center, taking advantage of White's delayal of c4 and prepares to target White's b2-pawn with ...Qb6. }
3. e3
{ Black was threatening to obtain a central pawn majority with 3...cxd4, so White supports his d4-pawn. }
3... Nc6
{ Black increases the pressure on the d4-pawn. An advantage of this move order is that dxc5 can be met by ...e5 followed by ...Bxc5, although this doesn't greatly matter because dxc5 is fine for Black, so 3...Nf6 is equally good. I prefer the 3...Nc6 move order because in the dxc5 complications, Bb5 is an option and things can be a bit different without the inclusion of Nf3 and ...Nf6, I'd rather only go into them if White commits to Nf3  (possibly preparing dxc5 by preventing ...e5)  so that I can play ...Nf6 and transpose into previously studied lines. }
4. c3 Nf6
{ Black prepares ...Qb6 by defending his d5-pawn.   4...Qb6  5.Qb3  c4  6.Qc2 !   It's worth mentioning that after  6.Qc2  Black can prepare  ...Bf5  with  6...Nf6  , but then White can play  7.Nd2  and White's a1-rook isn't as exposed , defusing one of the main points behind  ...Qb6.  6...Bf5  can be met by  7.Qxf5 !  where the  d5  and c4-pawns will drop off , giving White at least enough compensation for the exchange. Note that Black would not have been able to play  ...Qxb2  even if Black had played  ...Nf6  instead of  ...Nc6  because of  Qc8  checkmate. }
5. dxc5 { 5.Nd2  is stronger. } 5... e5
{ Black will win his pawn back by playing ...Bxc5 and has a better position due to his central pawn majority. }
