[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Annotated games"]
[Black "London with 5.c3 Qb6 6.Qb3 c4 7.Qc2: Gata Kamsky vs. Vladimir Akopian"]
[Result "*"]

{ This was a game between GM Gata Kamsky  (2692 FIDE, one of the world's leading London System specialists)  and GM Vladimir Akopian  (2698 FIDE)  , played in 2009. }
1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Bf4 c5 4. e3 Nc6 5. c3
{ Although  5.c3  is the mainline , it is inaccurate.  5.Nbd2  is stronger. }
5... Qb6
{ Seizing the initiative ! Black threatens to take the b2-pawn. White can't afford to sac it because Black would be able to play ...Qxc3 afterward  (picking up a second pawn)  and return home with ...Qa5-d8. }
6. Qb3 c4
{ Gaining space and forcing White to make a decision regarding his queen. } 7.
Qc2
{ 7.Qxb6  axb6  favors Black as he has the a-file and can start a queenside attack with  ...b5-b4. }
7... Bf5
{ Gaining a tempo. The tactical justification is that Qxf5 loses to ...Qxb2, picking up the a1-rook. }
8. Qc1
{ 8.Qxf5  Qxb2  Black will prevent  Qc2  with  ...e6  or  ...g6  (forcing White's queen away, as ...Qxa1 would be met with Qc2 if Black plays ...Qxa1 first)  (followed by ...Qxa1 with a material advantage.) }
8... h6
{ Black preserves his bishop pair, preparing to meet Nh4 with ...Bh7.   8...e6  is recommended in this repertoire , but the character of position after  8...h6  is similar. Although  ...h6  isn't forced , it is a thematic idea in this structure and there is a reasonable chance that they will transpose into each other if Black plays  ...h6  soon after  ...e6. }
9. h3 e6
{ Black already has a better position as he has a space advantage on the queenside without compensation for White. Black's plan is to rapidly develop  (...Be7, ...O-O)  and attack on the queenside  (...Rfc8, ...Qd8, ...b5, ...a5, ...b4)  . }
10. Nbd2 Be7 11. Be2 O-O 12. O-O Rfc8 13. Re1 Qd8 14. Bd1 b5
{ Black is following his plan and White has no counterplay because he has no compensation for Black's queenside space advantage. Black's has a huge advantage and objectively his winning chances are probably higher than White's drawing chances. }
15. Bc2 b4
{ Black has many ways of implementing his queenside attack.   15...Bxc2  16.Qxc2  b4  is also strong.   Black can also prepare  ...b4  with  15...a5. }
16. Bxf5 { 16.e4  dxe4  and Black gets the d5-outpost for his knight. } 16...
exf5 17. Ne5 Bd6 { 17...a5  is also strong. } 18. Qc2 Ne4
{ 18...Ne7  might be more accurate. After  18...Ne4  , eventually  f3  will be played and after the exchange on  d2  the f5-pawn is still exposed. The engine claims that Black is better by at least 1 pawn. }
19. f3
{ White provokes complications which favor Black in an attempt to create counterplay.   Keeping the tension with  19.Rad1  is probably more resilient but Black is still much better and can improve his position with  19...Ne7  , among other moves , and soon continue his queenside attack. }
19... Bxe5 20. dxe5
{ 20.Bxe5  Nc5 !  Black prepares  ...Nd3  and  21.dxc5  Nxe5  favors Black. }
20... Nc5 21. Qxf5 Nd3
{ 21...Ne7  followed by  ...Nd3  is more accurate to avoid  e6.  Black's positional advantage and queenside initiative should be objectively winning. }
22. e6 fxe6 23. Qxe6+ Kh8
{ Black can play ...Nxb2 and ...Qa5 with a powerful queenside initiative. It's not clear if White is able to defend this with best play. }
24. Kh2
{ According to the engine ,  24.Re2  offered better defending chances based on the idea  24...Nxb2  25.Ne4 !   Though  24.Re2  is the best defense , Black still has serious winning chances and can keep his initiative with  24...Qa5. }
24... Nxb2 { White's queenside is collapsing, Black's position is won. } 25.
cxb4 Nd3 26. b5 Nxf4 27. exf4 Nd4 28. Qg6 Qf8 29. Nf1 Qxf4+ 30. Kh1 Nxb5 31.
