[White "Annotated games"]
[Black "2.Bf4 London mainline with 5.Nd2: Bouwe Boschma vs. Miroslaw Woznica"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5 3. e3 Nf6
{ 3...Nc6  is recommended in this repertoire , but both moves are equally strong and are likely to transpose. }
4. c3 Nc6 5. Nd2
{ The most accurate move. White prepares for ...Qb6 by giving his a1-rook some breathing room.   5.Nf3  Qb6 !  6.Qb3  c4  7.Qc2  Bf5 !  and if  8.Qxf5  then  8...Qxb2  wins. }
5... Bf5
{ Black develops his light-squared bishop outside the pawn chain before he plays ...e6.   5...Qb6  isn't as effective when White already played  Nd2  because after  6.Qb3  c4  7.Qc2  Black doesn't have the immediate  ...Bf5  as  Ra1  isn't trapped. This gives White time to threaten to undermine Black's pawn chain with  e4  and/or  b3  with the initiative. }
6. Ngf3
{ The game could have transposed into my recommended line by playing the  6.Qb3  Qc8  7.Ngf3  move order. I recommend  7...c4  but it is likely to transpose after Black plays  ...e6. }
6... e6
{ I recommend  6...Qb6 !  in this repertoire where  7.Qb3  c4 !  will likely lead to a similar structure as in this game. }
7. Qb3 Qc8
{ Black defends his b7-pawn. An advantage of ...Qc8 over ...Qd7 is that Nf3-e5 doesn't come with tempo on Black's queen. }
8. h3 c4
{ Gaining space without losing time, as White's queen must retreat. Black plans to rapidly develop  (...Be7, ...O-O)  , possibly preserve his light-squared bishop  (...h6 prepares to meet Nh4 with ...Bh7)  and a queenside pawn storm where Black has the initiative. }
9. Qd1 h6
{ The main reason why Black is the one who is fighting for the advantage in this pawn structure is because he has a queenside space advantage and White is the one who has to prove that he has some kind of compensation for Black's extra space. White usually doesn't have compensation and this game is no exception, Black already has the advantage. }
10. Be2 b5 11. O-O Be7 12. Qc1 a5 13. Bd1 a4
{ More standard is ...b4, but ...a4 is also a thematic idea. Black threatens to play ...b4 followed by ...a3  (or sometimes ...a3 right away)  , provoking White to play a3. After White plays a3, the queenside will be closed, but Black will have the b3-outpost for his knight. After ...Na5-b3, White will be more or less obliged to exchange on b3, increasing Black's space advantage after he recaptures with his a-pawn. After this happens Black can prepare to sacrifice a minor piece on a3 for 2 connected passed pawns. As these passed pawns are already quite advanced, Black is often winning after this happens. White has no counterplay as he has no favorable imbalance anywhere on the board; White has no compensation for Black's space advantage. }
14. a3
{ If White doesn't play a3, he will have to allow ...b4  (with the threat of ...a3)  , or even the immediate ...a3. If White had played a3 after ...b4, then Black can exchange on either c3 or a3 and invade on the b-file, possibly even play the thematic plug sacrifice ...Rb8-b3  (if White takes on b3, Black usually should recapture with the c-pawn to obtain play against White's backward c-pawn and the c4-square)  . }
14... Na5
{ Black continues with his plan to plant a knight on b3, obtain a strong b3-pawn, and prepare to sacrifice on a3  (for instance, tripling major pieces down the a-file, possibly ...Nd7-b6-a4)  and later break through with ...b4  (after sacrificing with ...Bxa3 for 2 pawns)  . White has no defense against this plan, especially since if he plays passively on the queenside, Black can  (other than continue preparing the sacrifice)  possibly create a second weakness on the kingside or center. }
15. Bc2 Nb3 16. Nxb3 axb3 17. Bxf5 exf5 18. Qd1
{ White makes Black's plan easier by loosening his control over the a3-square, but White wouldn't have been able to successfully defend with passive play anyways as Black could make an Alekhine's gun  (trippling major pieces with the queen in the back)  on the a-file to prepare the ...Bxa3 sacrifice. }
18... O-O 19. Qe2 Re8 20. Rad1
{ Allowing the ...Bxa3 sacrifice ! Now Black doesn't need any more preparation, he can sacrifice on a3 right away. }
20... Bxa3 21. bxa3 Rxa3
{ Black's position is won. He will bring his major pieces to the queenside, centralize with ...Ne4, break through with ...b4, and  (after cxb4)  push his passed pawns to victory. }
22. Nd2 Ra2 23. Qe1 Qe6 24. Rb1 Ne4 25. Nxe4 fxe4 26. Qd1 Rea8 27. Be5 Rc2 28.
Rc1 Rxc1 29. Qxc1 Qe7 30. Qe1 f6 31. Bg3 Ra2 32. h4 b4
{ White resigns. If White had captured on b4, Black could easily win back the pawn with ...Ra4  (or just play ...Qa7 with ...b2 and ...Ra1)  and push his c and b-pawns for a win. It is often true that 2 connected passed pawns on the 6th rank are stronger than a rook, and here White only has a bishop to compensate. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Annotated games"]
[Black "London with 5.c3 Qb6 6.Qb3 c4 7.Qxb6 axb6 8.Nbd2: Anthony Mongiello vs. Anton Smirnov"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Bf4 c5 4. e3 Nc6 5. c3 Qb6 6. Qb3 c4 7. Qxb6
{ 7.Qc2  is stronger , though Black is still better after  7...Bf5 !  8.Qc1  e6. }
7... axb6
{ Black has a better endgame because of his queenside space advantage and the open a-file. Black's doubled b-pawns are not a serious weakness because they aren't isolated, they even help increase Black's queenside initiative with the plan of ...b5-b4  (according to the principles 'attack a pawn chain at its base' and 'attack in the direction of your pawn chain/space advantage')  . }
8. Nbd2 b5
{ The key move ! Black prepares to play ...b4, challenging White's queenside pawn chain. cxb4 ...Nxb4 improves Black's piece activity and makes the c4-pawn stronger  (especially after a later ...b5-b4)  while allowing ...bxc3 followed by ...b5-b4 will make Black's c-pawn passed. Black has a queenside initiative and White does not have compensation. It's worth mentioning that a3 doesn't prevent ...b4 because White's a3-pawn would be pinned.   8...Bf5  isn't as accurate because after  9.a3  b5  White has time to move his rook out of the way , dealing with the threat of  ...b4  by unpinning. Admittedly , Black is still better and has the dangerous plan  ...Nd7-b6-a4  , but his advantage is smaller than it would have been if he played  8...b5. }
9. Be2
{ 9.a3  aims to prevent  9...b4!  but doesn't succeed. White can't take twice on  b4  because his a-pawn is pinned. }
9... b4
{ Black's structural plan is to exchange on c3 followed by ...b5 and ...b4 to obtain a passed c-pawn. Since White can't stop this plan and will have no compensation for Black's passed c-pawn, Black's position is close to strategically winning. }
10. O-O e6
{ 10...bxc3  and  10...Bf5 !  also favor Black. I prefer  10...Bf5  over the move chosen in the game because Black will develop his bishop outside the pawn chain before playing  ...e6  , though Black still has a huge advantage after the move chosen in the game. }
11. Ne5 Nxe5 12. Bxe5
{ 12.dxe5  Nd7  13.e4  is critical , but Black is still better after  13...bxc3  14.bxc3  Nc5. }
12... Nd7 13. Nf3
{ White could have kept his bishop pair with  13.Bg3  , but he is still lacking a good way to defend his queenside after  13...b5. }
13... Nxe5 14. Nxe5 f6 15. Nf3 b5
{ While Black's position is won after  15...b5  , an easier win was  15...bxc3  because after  16.bxc3  Ra3 !  White is forced to play the passive  17.Rfc1.  Both of White's rooks are passive and Black can play  ...Bd6  ,  ...Kd7  , and  ...b5-b4. }
16. Nd2 f5
{ Black prevents  e4.  This approach is a safe road to victory , although  16...bxc3  17.bxc3  b4  was simple and strong. }
17. f4 bxc3 18. bxc3 b4
{ Breakthrough ! Black could have prepared this further  (White can't prevent ...b4)  with ...Ra3 and ...Bd6, but if it's clearly winning, why not play it ? }
19. Rfc1 Bd7 20. cxb4
{ Black would have provoked this exchange with ...Ra3 if White didn't play it. }
20... Bxb4
{ Black has the bishop pair and a passed c-pawn. White's pieces are passive and White's a-pawn is likely to drop off at some point. The win for Black is now a matter of technique. }
21. Nb1 Ke7 22. Nc3 Ra3 23. Nd1 Bd2 24. Rc2 Bxe3+ 25. Nxe3 Rxe3 26. Bf3 Rb8 27.
Kf2 Ra3 28. Re1 Kd6 29. Re3 Rba8 30. Rxa3 Rxa3 31. g4 Ba4 32. Rb2 c3 33. Rb1
Rxa2+ 34. Ke3 Rxh2 35. Rc1 c2 36. Be2 fxg4 37. Bxg4 h5 38. Be2 h4 39. Kd2 Bb5
40. Re1 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Annotated games"]
[Black "London with 5.c3 Qb6 6.Qb3 c4 7.Qxb6 axb6 8.Na3: Kevin McCarthy vs. Peter Wells"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. Bf4 c5 4. c3 Nc6 5. e3 Qb6 6. Qb3 c4 7. Qxb6 axb6 8. Na3
{ The most critical move, aiming to prevent ...b5. } 8... Bf5
{ Black wants to play ...e6 to challenge Na3  (by threatening ...Bxa3)  but that would lock his light-squared bishop inside the pawn chain. Therefore, he first develops his bishop outside the pawn chain, preparing to play ...e6. Black's light-squared bishop is strongest on f5 because if White plays Nb5 and meets ...Ra5 with a4, Black has the option of playing ...Bc2. Black also controls the b1-square, making ...Ra5-b5 stronger in some cases  (if White exchanges or moves Na3)  . }
9. Nb5
{ White threatens Nc7+.   9.Nh4  is more critical but Black is still better , especially after the recommended  9...g6 !  For more information , see the  9.Nh4  variation. }
9... Ra5 { Challenging the knight. } 10. a4
{ Loses a pawn to ...Bc2, but White doesn't have anything better.   10.Na3  e6 !  Black threatens  ...Bxa3.  11.Nb1  Bxb1  12.Rxb1  Rxa2  Black has won a pawn.   10.Nc7+  Kd7  White's c7-knight is trapped and Black will try to remove the defender   Bf4  (with ...Nh5 and/or ...e6 with ...Bd6.) }
10... Bc2 { White has no way to defend his a4-pawn. } 11. Na3
{ White panics, making the technical task easier for Black. Losing 2 tempi with Nb5-a3 guarantees that White won't have compensation for the pawn.   11.Be2  is most critical , hoping that White's lead in development will partially compensate for the lost pawn. Black can grab the pawn with  11...Rxa4  , but White has sufficient compensation after  12.Kd2 !  Bb3  13.Nc7+  Kd7  14.Rxa4  with  Ra1  and  Ng5  coming.   After  11.Be2  , Best is to just continue developing with  11...e6 !  and the a4-pawn is a long-term weakness. White has nothing better than  12.Bd1  Bxd1  13.Kxd1  but Black has the advantage because he can castle and White's a-pawn is weak , Black's plan is  ...Be7  with  ...Ne4  and  ...O-O  with  ...Rha8. }
11... Bxa4
{ Black is up a pawn for no compensation and still has a queenside initiative. Black's winning plan is to rapidly develop and push his b-pawns, hopefully trading both b-pawns for White's b and c-pawns, leaving Black with an extra passed c-pawn. }
12. Bc7 Ra6 13. Nd2 e6 14. b4
{ Desperation, but White no longer had a defense. } 14... Nxb4
{ Black sacrifices a piece for 2 connected passed pawns. These pawns are very strong, especially the c4-pawn, and White has no easy way to blockade them. As shown by Bouwe Boschma vs. Miroslaw Woznica, this thematic London sacrifice tends to be decisive when White allows it. }
15. Rb1
{ 15.cxb4  loses to  15...Bxb4.   15...Bd7  16.Nc2  Rxa1+  17.Nxa1  Bxb4  also wins. }
15... Nc2+ 16. Nxc2 Bxc2 17. Rc1 Ba4 18. Be2 b5 19. O-O b4 20. cxb4 Bxb4 21.
Nb1 b5 22. f3 O-O *

