[White "Annotated games"]
[Black "The London Qxb6 endgame (White prevents a quick ...b4): Vladimir Petkov vs. Momchil Nikolov"]
[Result "*"]

{ This was a rapid game played in 2016. White was rated 2474 FIDE and Black was rated 2559 FIDE. }
1. d4 Nf6
{ This repertoire recommends the  1...d5  move order , but the game soon transposed into my recommended line. }
2. Bf4 d5 3. e3 c5 4. c3 Nc6 5. Nd2 Bf5 6. Ngf3 Qb6 7. Qb3
{ 7.Nh4  is more critical, the complications that arise after  7...Bd7  8.Qb3  c4  9.Qc2  Nh5  10.Bg3  Nxg3  11.hxg3  g5  12.Nhf3  g4  are unclear. They might favor Black, but 7.Qb3 definitely favors Black. }
7... c4 8. Qxb6 axb6
{ Black has an advantage in this endgame due to his queenside space advantage. Black plans to advance on the queenside with ...b5-b4. }
9. a3 b5 10. Rc1
{ White prevents ...b4. This is a more ideal version of the endgame than if White had allowed ...b4, but Black still has the advantage and intends to attack on the queenside. Black's plan, after preparation and development, is to transfer his f6-knight to a4   ...Nd7-b6-a4  to target the b2-pawn. Black might later sacrifice with ...b4 to open the queenside, or sacrifice a piece for connected 2 pawns  (after ...Na4, this could happen with ...Nxb2 and ...Bxa3 or ...Bxa3 and ...Nxc3)  . }
10... h6 { Black preserves his bishop pair, as Nh4 can be met with ...Bh7. }
11. h3 e6 12. Be2 Nd7 { Black resumes his plan. } 13. g4 Bh7
{ White has no counterplay and has to hope to defend for a draw. } 14. Bd1
{ Be2-d1 is a standard maneuver that White often tries in this pawn structure to prepare for ...Nb6-a4. The idea is that White can trade bishops with Bc2  (then White can defend his b2-pawn with his rook)  and also has the option to meet ...Na4 with Bxa4. Black is still much better, White needed this defensive maneuver to have surviving chances. }
14... Nb6 15. Bc2
{ 15.O-O  Na4  16.Bxa4  bxa4  with ...Ra6-b6 to target the b2-pawn. Black can finish his development with ...Kd7 and ...Be7/...Bd6 and can double rooks by transferring the h-rook to b4   ...Ra8-a5-b4  . White's only advantage is the e5-outpost, which Black can neutralize with ...f6. }
15... Bxc2 16. Rxc2 b4
{ Breakthrough ! Black takes advantage of White's lack of back-rank protection. }
17. O-O
{ 17.axb4  Ra1+  wins a piece due to the skewer.   17.cxb4  Nxb4  White can't take the knight without allowing ...Ra1+  (winning the sacrificed material back with interest)  and Rc1+ allows ...Nd3+. White's only try is  18.Rc3  but after  18...Na4   18...Nd3+  is also strong.  19.axb4  Nxc3  20.bxc3  Ra1+  Black wins material. }
17... b3
{ Black has a decisive space advantage. White can't prevent the thematic London sacrifice of a piece for 2 connected passed pawns. }
18. Rcc1 Na4
{ 18...Bxa3 !?  19.bxa3  Rxa3  is better for Black, but not a clean winning line because White a can trade rooks with Ra1. It's better to prepare this sacrifice with ...Na4 so that Black can also win the c3-pawn, as White can't prevent ...Bxa3. }
19. Rb1 Bxa3 20. bxa3 Nxc3 21. Rb2 Ne2+ 22. Kg2 Nxf4+ 23. exf4 Rxa3
{ Black has 3 pawns for the piece, and 2 of them are connected passed pawns that are already close to the promotion squares. The win is simple, Black just needs to bring his pieces to the queenside and push his passed pawns. }
24. Rc1 Ra2 25. Rbb1 Na5 26. Nf1 b5 27. f5 O-O 28. Ne5 b4 29. Ne3 b2 30. Re1 c3
31. Nd7 Rc8 32. Nb6 Rc6 33. Nexd5 Rxb6 34. Nxb6 c2 35. Kf3 Nb3 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Annotated games"]
[Black "London with 5.Nbd2 Bf5 6.dxc5 e6 7.Nd4: Son Nguyen vs. Mikhael Mchedlishvili"]
[Result "*"]

{ This game was played between 2 GMs at the 2017 World Rapid. White was rated 2630 FIDE and Black was rated 2603 FIDE. }
1. d4 Nf6
{ This course recommends the  1...d5  move order , but  1...Nf6  is likely to transpose if you meet  2.Nf3  with  2...d5. }
2. Nf3 d5 3. Bf4 c5 4. e3 Nc6 5. Nbd2
{ The most accurate move order , avoiding the  5.c3  Qb6  lines.   The idea is that  5...Qb6  can be met by  6.dxc5 !  where after  ...Qxb2  there is no pawn hanging on  c3  and White has the option of playing  c4. }
5... Bf5
{ Black aims to obtain a small advantage in an almost symmetrical position due to his queenside space advantage and more active queenside knight. Black intends to consolidate his c5-pawn with ...e6 next, so White should strike with dxc5 now if he wants to fight for the advantage. }
6. dxc5
{ Critical. White aims to exploit the loose bishop on f5 by meeting ...e6 with Nd4  (threatening to prevent ...b6 with Nxc6 followed by b4)  .   6.c3  Qb6 !  White's c3-pawn is hanging after  ...Qxb2  , so Black seizes the moment to fight for the initiative. This variation is covered in the theory section. }
6... e6 7. Nd4
{ Critical. White threatens to keep his extra pawn with Nxc6 followed by b4.   7.Nb3  Bxc5  8.Nxc5  Qa5+  9.c3  Qxc5 }
7... Bxc5 { Black wins his pawn back at the cost of the bishop pair. } 8. Nxf5
exf5
{ This is a dynamically balanced position where both sides have chances to play for a win. White has the bishop pair and fewer pawn islands  (static advantages)  . Black has more space and a lead in development  (dynamic advantages; although space can also be static)  . From the theoretical point of view, this is the critical branching point. White needs to find something convincing on the next move with a clear plan and counter against Black's main options in order to fight for the advantage. In my opinion, this variation is the most testing against my recommended London approach. }
9. Nb3
{ White gains a tempo attacking Black's c5-bishop and increases his control over the blockading d4-square. The consequence of 9. Nb3 is that White loosened his control over the e4-square, making ...Ne4 more dangerous as White is not able to exchange this knight with Nxe4. }
9... Bb6
{ Black keeps his bishop in contact with the d4-square. This is an important idea because Black might want to liquidate his isolated queen pawn with ...d4 later.   Stockfish 10 claims that  9...Bd6  is also fine for Black , but in my opinion  9...Bd6  is less ambitious because it offers to exchange minor pieces , which is against the spirit of playing with an isolated queen pawn unless there is a clear gain from the exchange. }
10. Be2
{ GM Shakhriyar Mamedyarov once played  10.Bd3  and won against GM Vladislav Artemiev. Black responded with the passive  10...Qd7.  This move is passive because Black's queen is restricted on the light-squares by the  d5  and  f5  pawns. Black's queen would be more active on dark-squares , for example , on  e7.  Black had multiple strong alternatives , for example ,  10...g6  (following Capablanca's rule)  (,)   10...Ne4  ,   or even the pawn sacrifice  10.Bd3  O-O  11.Bxf5  d4. }
10... Ne4
{ Black's knight occupies the central outpost square. Now the dynamic ...g5 is in the air. }
11. Bf3 O-O
{ Black remains flexible, increasing his lead in development.   Black was also at least equal with the developing  11...Rc8.   The dynamic  11...g5 !  was also strong. Black can fight for the initiative with  12.Bxe4  gxf4 !   or  12.Bg3  h5 ! }
12. O-O Re8
{ Black continues developing. His claim is that his superior piece activity and space advantage compensates for White's superior pawn structure and bishop pair, even if there aren't immediate tactics. }
13. h3
{ This slow move increases Black's dynamic advantage.   According to Stockfish 10 , the most critical move was  13.a4.  Black had several good options including the positional options  13...a6  ,   13...Rc8  ,   and  13...h6  which proves that Black doesn't need a knockout blow to be fine. Most dangerous for White is probably  13.a4  g5  14.Bg3  d4 !  where Black is fighting for the initiative. }
13... d4
{ Black trades his isolated pawn and offers trades in the center.   13...g5 !  14.Bh2  d4 !  is probably an improvement as Black gained space with tempo before playing  ...d4.  Black isn't scared of  15.Bxe4  because White would no longer have the bishop pair after  15...Rxe4  and could even fix his pawn structure with  15...dxe4  if he wanted to.   Black could also have kept the tension with  13...Qf6  , preparing  ...Rad8  with  ...g5  and  ...Ne5.  Black is okay with White grabbing the d5-pawn because taking the pawn would lose time and open the position for Black's lead in development. Black could respond to  14.Qxd5  with the tactical  14...Nxf2 !  with the idea of  ...g5  followed by  ...Bxe3.   or the simple  14...Rad8  with compensation }
14. exd4 Nxd4
{ Black is the only one who can be better here as he traded his isolated d-pawn and has superior piece activity in the center. White's bishop pair isn't more active than Black's bishop and knight, especially since White's light-squared bishop is restricted by Black's e4-knight. Black's doubled f-pawns are not weak because they are not isolated and there is no way to target them. Admittedly, Black likely doesn't have any objective advantage here, but he was the one who chose to go for the dry equalizer and had dynamic options earlier. White, being down on activity, is the one who has to prove equality here. }
15. c3
{ Too slow. White should have exchanged Black's centralized knight.   15.Nxd4  is probably best after which Black should play  15...Bxd4  as he only wants to trade queens if White will make a concession to trade them.  16.c3  Bb6  and White must increase Black's rook activity with  17.Qxd8  Raxd8  to trade queens , where Black will have a better endgame , but White doesn't have to trade queens. He can keep the tension with  17.a4  and there isn't an easy way to exploit Black's piece activity as the lead in activity is small , 2 pairs of minor pieces have been traded , and White's bishop pair almost compensates. }
15... Nxb3
{ Black is still better after this move , but  15...Qh4 !  was more energetic , especially since Black would have the option of meeting  16.Bh2  with  Nxf2 !  where  17.Rxf2  loses to  Nxb3  where  Rf2  will soon be lost. }
16. axb3 Qh4
{ Black targets the f2-pawn and has a powerful initiative due to his superior center control and lead in development. }
17. Bxe4
{ 17.Be3  Bxe3  18.fxe3  is a structural concession. White's e3-pawn is weaker than Black's f5-pawn because the e3-pawn is isolated. }
17... Rxe4 18. Be3 Bxe3 19. fxe3
{ Black can play this position for a win without risk by targeting White's isolated e3-pawn. Black's f5-pawn isn't very weak because he can protect it with ...g6. }
19... g6 20. Qd2
{ 20.Qd7 !  offered some defending chances as White needs active counterplay. Black is still much better and can choose between the positional  20...Re7   or the dynamic options  20...Rxe3   and  20...Qg5. }
20... Qe7
{ White's position is lost. Black will win the isolated e3-pawn with superior piece activity. White can't afford to trade off all of the major pieces after Black wins the e3-pawn because the king and pawn endgame up a pawn would be winning, so White will have to make concessions to avoid trades, which will allow Black's pieces to invade with a decisive initiative.   21.Rfe1  loses to both  21...Re8   and  21...Rd8  22.Qf2  Rd3. }
21. Rad1 Rxe3 22. Qd7 Re8 23. Qxe7 R8xe7
{ Black is up a pawn with superior piece activity. The rest is a matter of technique. }
24. Rd2 Kg7 25. b4 a6 26. Kf2 f4 27. Ra1 g5 28. Ra5 Kg6 29. Rad5 f6 30. b5 axb5
31. Rxb5 h5 32. Rb4 Kf5 33. Rd5+ R3e5 34. Rbd4 g4 35. hxg4+ hxg4 36. c4 Rxd5
37. Rxd5+ Re5 38. Rd7 g3+ 39. Kf1 b5 40. Rc7 bxc4 41. Rxc4 Kg4 42. Rc8 Rb5 43.
