[Black "London with 4.dxc5: Adam Rakos vs. Istvan Taskovits"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 d5 2. d4 Nf6 3. Bf4 c5 4. dxc5 Nc6
{ 4...e6  is recommended in this course but  4...Nc6  is also strong. This game soon transposed into one of my recommended lines. }
5. c3 e6 6. b4
{ White unsuccessfully tries to keep his extra pawn. 6. e3 is safer, though Black would have at least equality after 6... Bxc5. }
6... a5 { Attacking the base of the pawn chain. } 7. Nd4
{ White's most popular move. The idea is that White can meet ...axb4 with Nxc6 and after ...bxc6, Black no longer has ...b6 to challenge White's queenside pawn chain. }
7... axb4 8. Nxc6 bxc6 9. cxb4 Ng4
{ The key move ! White is up a pawn for now but is weak on the long diagonal. Black threatens to play ...Qf6 with a fork on Bf4 and Ra1. Black might also play for mate due to the weak f2-square. The advantage of ...Ng4 instead of ...Ne4 here is that Black might play ...e5. This is especially relevant in the variation 10. e3 Qf6 and White can't play 11. Qd4 due to 11...e5. }
10. Qd4
{ White controls the f6-square in an attempt to prevent ...Qf6.   10.Bg3  Qf6  11.Nd2  h5  12.h4  Ra3!  gives Black a winning initiative. }
10... Be7
{ Black prepares both ...Bf6 and ...e5.   This repertoire's recommended line is  10...e5  11.Bxe5  Nxe5  12.Qxe5+  Be7  but  10...Be7  is equally strong and the game soon transposed into the recommended line by playing the  ...e5  pawn sacrifice. }
11. Nc3
{ White blocks the a1-h8 diagonal so that ...Bf6 is no longer a skewer. } 11...
e5
{ The key move ! Black sacrifices a pawn for the bishop pair and to further expose White's queen. Black is playing for dynamics because he already sacrificed a pawn, he should prioritize the initiative over material. }
12. Bxe5 Nxe5 13. Qxe5 O-O
{ Black's huge lead in development, bishop pair, central space advantage, and White's exposed queen more than compensate for the sacrificed 2 pawns. Objectively, Black's initiative is decisive. Black's winning plan is to rapidly finish his development with ...Bf6, ...Bf5, advance in the center with ...d4  (and possibly ...d3)  , and centralize with ...Qd5 and possibly ...Rad8. White is too far behind in development to defend against this, especially since a lot of Black's plan comes with tempo. }
14. a4
{ White can't safely develop his kingside.   14.e3  Bf6 !  wins the knight on  c3  as  e3  interfered with the communication between the  g3  and c3-squares;  Qg3  no longer defends White's c3-knight.   14.g3  Bf6  White no longer has the g3-square available for his queen so to defend his knight he must play  15.Qe3  but  15...d4 !  wins the c3-knight anyways. }
14... Re8 15. Qg3 Bf5 16. h4
{ 16.e3  Bf6 !  and White's queen is no longer defending the c3-knight and Black can meet  17.Rc1  with  17...d4. }
16... Bf6 17. Ra3 d4 18. Nd1 d3 19. Qf4 Qd5
{ Black has centralized his pieces. All that's now needed is to open the position with ...dxe2 and calculate the winning tactics. }
20. Qd2 dxe2 21. Bxe2 Qxg2 22. Rf1 Rad8 { Black has a crushing attack. } 23.
Qf4 Qd5 24. Qc1 Qd4 25. Rg1 Qxb4+ 26. Kf1 Rd2 27. Re3 Rxe3 28. Nxe3 Bh3+ 29.
Ng2 Bxh4 30. Qe1 Qb2 31. a5 Rc2 32. a6 Rc1 33. a7 Rxe1+ 34. Kxe1 Qc1+ 35. Bd1
Qc3+ 36. Kf1 Qa1 37. Ke2 Bxg2 *

