[White "Annotated games"]
[Black "2.Bf4 London with 3.e4: Alexander Velikanov vs. Conrad Holt"]
[Result "*"]

{ This game was played in the 2016 UT Dallas Fall Open between FM Alexander Velikanov and GM Conrad Holt }
1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5 3. e4
{ White sacrifices a pawn in an attempt to obtain the initiative.   The main idea is that after  3...dxe4  White has  4.d5  with a space advantage and easy development. }
3... Nc6 { Black declines the gambit, opting to focus on development. } 4. exd5
Qxd5
{ Black has a lead in development and White's center is falling apart, so White needs something concrete to justify his approach. }
5. Nc3
{ White sacrifices the d4-pawn, hoping for sufficient counterplay after Nd5. }
5... Qxd4 { Black grabs a pawn and threatens ...Qxf4. } 6. Nd5
{ White threatens Nc7+ and defends his bishop.   6.Qxd4  cxd4  7.Nd5  e5  8.Nc7+  Kd8  9.Nxa8  exf4  is a similar exchange sacrifice to what happened in the game. }
6... e5
{ Black sacrifices the exchange, knowing that he can later win his material back as White's knight will be trapped in the corner. }
7. Nc7+ Kd8 8. Nxa8 exf4
{ Black has excellent compensation for the exchange in the form of his space advantage, lead in development, bishop pair, extra pawn, and White's trapped a8-knight. Black will soon win back the knight with ...Bd7 followed by ...Kc8-b8-xa8 with at least equal chances. }
9. c3
{ A mistake, as Nf3 would also have forced Black to trade queens. Nf3 is more accurate than c3 because Nf3 develops a piece and c3 does not.   The main line is  9.Nf3  Qxd1+  10.Rxd1+  Bd7  and White can't stop  ...Kc8-b8-xa8  , although before playing  ...Kb8  , Black should defend his d7-bishop with  ...Nf6.  It's worth mentioning that Black has won every master-game that reached this position and Stockfish 10 , which tends to undervalue long-term sacrifices , claims  (at depth 49)  (that Black has several ways to keep full compensation)  ('0.00')  (.) }
9... Qxd1+ 10. Rxd1+ Bd7
{ As Black already has enough compensation for the exchange material-wise  (I generally consider an exchange sacrifice to be roughly 1.5 pawns worth as long as there aren't a lot of open files for the rooks)  - he has a pawn and the bishop pair  (generally worth around half a pawn in open positions)  , White needs to find compensation for his trapped knight. If White fails to drum up enough counterplay for his trapped knight, his position will be lost. }
11. Nh3 Kc8 12. Bb5
{ Too slow. White allows ...Bxh3, damaging White's pawn structure and solving Black's problem of how to play ...Kb8 without losing his d7-bishop. White must act now if he wants to have any chances to save the game.   Stockfish 10 considers White's best chance to be  12.Nxf4  , but Black is much better  (possibly winning)  after  12...Nf6  or  12...Be7. The tempo that White lost on9.c3  was extremely costly , after the exchange sacrifice , the onus is on White to prove that he is fine as Black has a winning plan if White doesn't have something concrete. }
12... Bg4 13. f3 Bxh3 14. gxh3 Nge7
{ White's a8-knight can't escape; Black focused on development to prevent any counterplay and plans to win White's a8-knight soon. White has no defense. }
15. a4 Nf5 16. a5 Be7 17. a6 Bh4+ 18. Ke2 Re8+ 19. Kd3 Kb8 20. axb7 Kxb7 21.
Ra1 Rxa8 22. Bxc6+ Kxc6 23. Ke4 g6 24. Kxf4 Re8 25. Ra6+ Kb5 26. Rha1 Ne3 27.
R1a5+ Kc4 28. Ra4+ Kb3
{ White resigned because he can't avoid ...g5 checkmate. } *

