[White "1...Nf6 and 1...f5"]
[Black "Black vs. London (1...Nf6 move order for KID players): 2.Bf4 d5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6
{ Not everybody meets 1.d4 with 1...d5, so I will show how to fight the London for King's Indian/Grunfeld players as well. }
2. Bf4 d5
{ Black is likely to transpose into previously studied lines.   The only critical line of independent value is  3.e3  c5  4.dxc5  , aiming to take advantage of the delay of  Nf3  and planning for a quick  Bb5. }
3. e3
{ 3.Nc3  c5 !  4.e3  cxd4  5.exd4  a6  transposes into a line which was covered via the  1...d5  move order with the difference that Black has played  ...Nf6  instead of  ...Nc6.  This difference doesn't really change much as Black intended on playing both in the near future and White has no way to punish the difference. }
3... c5 4. dxc5
{ Other lines are likely to transpose into previously studied lines.   4.c3  Nc6   4.Nf3  Nc6 }
4... e6
{ 4...Nc6  5.Bb5  is complex , relatively unclear , and White is likely to be well prepared if he is going to enter this line. I'd rather deviate earlier. }
5. b4
{ 5.Nf3  Bxc5  is at least equal for Black due to his central pawn majority. }
5... a5 { Challenging the base of White's pawn chain. } 6. c3 Bd7
{ 6...Nc6  7.Bb5 !  transposes into the variation Black avoided by playing  ...e6  instead of  ...Nc6.  The key move ! Black prepares to play ...axb4 followed by ...b6 without allowing Bb5. Since White has no defense against ...axb4 followed by ...b6, Black will win his pawn back with a good game.    There are hardly any games here , so you shouldn't expect your opponent to be well prepared. Regardless , players wishing to play this move order should investigate the following complications.  7.Nd2  The only critical move.  7...axb4  8.cxb4  b6  9.cxb6  Bxb4  10.Bc7  Qe7!   10...Qc8?  11.Rb1!  is better for White.  11.b7  This series of moves is the only critical line that White could try after  6...Bd7  Black has 2 options.  11...Ra3   11...Ra7  12.Bxb8  Rxb7  13.Bg3  Ne4!  14.Nf3  e5!  Black seems to have compensation for the piece in the form of his lead in development , center , and initiative. Is it sufficient? I'm not sure , and Stockfish keeps changing its mind , fluctuating between a White advantage and 0.00.  12.Bxb8  Ba4   12...O-O  is also playable and is worthy of investigation.   12...Ne4  is also playable and is worthy of investigation.  13.Be5!  Forced , according to the engine. Other moves allow Black to win White's queen or play  ...Qxb7  with a decisive initiative.  13...Qxb7   13...O-O  is a viable alternative according to Stockfish.  14.Qb1  Forced , according to the engine. White's queen would be too exposed on  c1  as Black could target it  (after castling)  with  ...Rc8.  14...d4  Black opens the position to try to exploit his lead in development.   14...O-O  is also playable. Stockfish 10 at depth 27 claims '0.00'.   14...Ne4  is also playable. Stockfish 10 at depth 27 claims '0.00'.   14...Bxd2+  is also playable. Stockfish 10 at depth 27 claims '0.00'.  15.Bxd4  Forced.   15.Bxf6  doesn't work because of  15...dxe3!  16.fxe3  Rxe3+  and Black will recapture on  f6  next because  17.Kf2  loses to  17...Qa7!   15.exd4  loses to  15...Ne4!  because  16.Nf3  can be met with  16...Rxf3  , revealing one of the main points behind  ...d4.  15...e5!  16.Bxe5  forced.  16...Bxd2+  17.Kxd2  Qd5+  18.Bd4  forced.  18...Ne4+   18...Qa5+  19.Ke2  and Black can give a perpetual check with  ...Qa6-a5  or  ...Bb5-c6.  19.Ke2  O-O  with unclear complications. Stockfish 10 claims that Black is at least equal   depth 31 claims that White must play  20.f3  not to be lost  (and can give a perpetual if he wants, so it's safe to say that he has sufficient compensation for the sacrificed piece.)   19...Bd1+  forces a perpetual.  20.Qxd1  Qb5+  21.Ke1  Qa5+  22.Ke2  Qb5+  with a draw. }
