[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1...Nf6 and 1...f5"]
[Black "Black vs. London (1...Nf6 move order for KID players): 2.Nf3 g6 3.Bf4 Bg7 4.Nc3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6
{ Not everybody meets 1.d4 with 1...d5, so I will show how to fight the London for King's Indian/Grunfeld players as well. }
2. Nf3 g6
{ 2...d5  would transpose into previously recommended lines from chapter 1 if White played  3.Bf4  , but King's Indian and Grunfeld players would likely not be happy with this approach as Black can be move ordered into a Queen's Gambit with  3.c4. }
3. Bf4 Bg7
{ The first tabiya of the KID version of the London. White has two main choices.   1  4.e3 with rapid development. This is the positional approach.   2  4.Nc3 intending Qd2 followed by Bh6, O-O-O, and h4-h5. This is the aggressive approach.   Black's general plan is to rapidly develop his pieces  (...O-O, ...d6, ...b6, ...Bb7, ...Nbd7, possibly ...Re8 to prepare for ...e5)  followed by a pawn break  (...c5 or ...e5)  to free his dark-squared bishop. Black should adjust his plan according to what White does, especially if he has concrete threats or makes positional concessions. }
4. Nc3
{ White focuses on dynamics by rapidly developing and preparing Qd2 and O-O-O with Bh6 and h4-h5. Playing e4 is another idea, but Black can prevent this with 4...d5. }
4... d5
{ Black prevents e4, which would force a transposition into a Pirc/Modern. 4...d5 also highlights the drawback of Nc3, as Nc3 tends to be misplaced in 1.d4 d5 structures if White plays Nc3 before c4 because the d5-pawn restricts the c3-knight. If White played c4 before Nc3, the pressure on the d5-pawn would make Nc3 have purpose. White needs dynamics to justify his approach or else Black will have at least equality through natural developing moves and the ...c5 break. }
5. Qd2
{ White prepares to trade dark-squared bishops with Bh6 followed by a kingside attack on the newly weakened dark-squares. }
5... O-O { Black focuses on development. } 6. Bh6
{ This approach would be more dangerous if Black didn't have something concrete. }
6... Ne4
{ The key move ! Black counters a flank attack with a blow in the center. If White plays 7.Nxe4 then 7...dxe4 hits Nf3, gaining a tempo and pressuring the d4-pawn.   Note that this resource isn't strong if White had played the  2.Bf4  move order because White's knight wouldn't have been on  f3  , making  Nxe4  stronger. For that reason , I think it's too dangerous to recommend  2...g6  against  2.Bf4  but it's okay to commit to  2...d5  against  2.Bf4  because White committed to a London. }
7. Qe3 Qd6
{ Flexible development. 7...Bf5 would allow a later g4 when White is trying to blast open the kingside. The concrete justification behind 7...Qd6 is that if White takes twice on e4  (after Bxg7)  then Black has ...Qb4+ regaining his pawn. If White castles queenside, Black can rapidly develop and pawn storm as fast as White can. Therefore, Black's position is at least equal.   8.Bxg7  Kxg7  9.O-O-O   9.Nxe4  dxe4  10.Qxe4  Qb4+  picks up the b2-pawn.  9...Nxc3  10.Qxc3  Black has good counterplay on the queenside and can play moves like  ...a5  ,  ...Bf5  ,  ...Nd7  , and continue the pawn storm while White's h4-h5 idea can always be met with  ...h5. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1...Nf6 and 1...f5"]
[Black "Black vs. London (1...Nf6 move order for KID players): 2.Nf3 g6 3.Bf4 Bg7 4.Nc3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6
{ Not everybody meets 1.d4 with 1...d5, so I will show how to fight the London for King's Indian/Grunfeld players as well. }
2. Nf3 g6
{ 2...d5 would transpose into previously recommended lines from chapter 1 if White played 3.Bf4, but King's Indian and Grunfeld players would likely not be happy with this approach as Black can be move ordered into a Queen's Gambit with 3.c4. }
3. Bf4 Bg7
{ The first tabiya of the KID version of the London. White has two main choices.   1  4.e3 with rapid development. This is the positional approach.   2  4.Nc3 intending Qd2 followed by Bh6, O-O-O, and h4-h5. This is the aggressive approach.   Black's general plan is to rapidly develop his pieces  (...O-O, ...d6, ...b6, ...Bb7, ...Nbd7, possibly ...Re8 to prepare for ...e5)  followed by a pawn break  (...c5 or ...e5)  to free his dark-squared bishop. Black should adjust his plan according to what White does, especially if he has concrete threats or makes positional concessions. }
4. Nc3
{ White focuses on dynamics by rapidly developing and preparing Qd2 and O-O-O with Bh6 and h4-h5. Playing e4 is another idea, but Black usually prevents this with 4...d5. }
4... d5
{ Black prevents e4, which would force a transposition into a Pirc/Modern. 4...d5 also highlights the drawback of Nc3, as Nc3 tends to be misplaced in 1.d4 d5 structures if White plays Nc3 before c4 as the d5-pawn restricts the c3-knight. If White hasn't played c4 before Nc3, there isn't pressure on the d5-pawn. White needs dynamics to justify his approach or else Black will have at least equality through natural developing moves and the ...c5 break. }
5. Qd2
{ White prepares to trade dark-squared bishops with Bh6 followed by a kingside attack on the newly weakened dark-squares. }
5... O-O { Black focuses on development. } 6. Bh6
{ This approach would be more dangerous if Black didn't have something concrete. }
6... Ne4
{ The key move ! Black counters a flank attack with a blow in the center. If White plays 7.Nxe4 then 7...dxe4 hits Nf3, gaining a tempo and pressuring the d4-pawn.   Note that this resource isn't strong if White had played the  2.Bf4  move order because White's knight wouldn't have been on  f3  , making  Nxe4  stronger. For that reason , I think it's too dangerous to recommend  2...g6  against  2.Bf4  but it's okay to commit to  2...d5  because White committed to a London. }
7. Nxe4 dxe4 8. Bxg7 Kxg7
{ 4.Nc3 was aimed at achieving dynamics and White has failed in his goal as Black has a space advantage and easier development with no serious weaknesses.   Black can meet  9.Ne5  with  9...c5   or  9...b5  (preparing ...f6 as White's knight has no good squares)  (with the initiative.)   9.Ng5  can be met with the simple  9...f5   or the strong counterattack  9...e5 ! }
