[Round "?"]
[White "1...Nf6 and 1...f5"]
[Black "Black vs. London (1...Nf6 move order for KID players): 2.Nf3 g6 3.Bf4 Bg7 4.e3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6
{ Not everybody meets 1.d4 with 1...d5, so I will show how to fight the London for King's Indian/Grunfeld players as well. }
2. Nf3 g6
{ 2...d5 would transpose into previously recommended lines from chapter 1 if White played 3.Bf4, but King's Indian and Grunfeld players would likely not be happy with this approach as Black can be move ordered into a Queen's Gambit with 3.c4. }
3. Bf4 Bg7
{ The first tabiya of the KID version of the London. White has two main choices.   1  4.e3 with rapid development. This is the positional approach.   2  4.Nc3 intending Qd2 followed by Bh6, O-O-O, and h4-h5. This is the aggressive approach.   Black's general plan is to rapidly develop his pieces  (...O-O, ...d6, ...b6, ...Bb7, ...Nbd7, possibly ...Re8 to prepare for ...e5)  followed by a pawn break  (...c5 or ...e5)  to free his dark-squared bishop. Black should adjust his plan according to what White does, especially if he has concrete threats or makes positional concessions. }
4. e3
{ The positional approach. It's worth mentioning that against other slow moves like c3 or Nbd2, Black can play the same plan. }
4... O-O 5. Be2
{ 5.Be2 is more accurate than 5.Bd3 because if White plays Bd3 against the KID approach, the ...e5 break becomes stronger as Black has the ...e4 fork after Bf4 moves. Note that Black will prioritize the ...e5 break over the ...c5 break if White plays Bd3 instead of Be2. The ...e5 break could be prepared by ...Nbd7 and ...Re8 or ...Qe8. }
5... d6
{ Consistent with the King's Indian. Black blunts White's 'London bishop'   Bf4  , controlling the e5-square and preparing the possible ...e5 and ...c5 breaks. }
6. h3
{ Black's approach is more or less universal at this point. The position is closed and White has no threats, so Black can continue with his plan regardless of what positional plan White chooses, though Black might want to adjust it in order to take advantage of any weaknesses/concessions that White makes. It's also worth mentioning that Black has lots of playable options here. }
6... b6
{ The most flexible. Black doesn't commit to either pawn break yet  (...e5 or ...c5)  and wants to finish his development with ...Bb7 and ...Nbd7 before deciding.   6...c5  is also strong. }
7. O-O Bb7
{ Black will play ...Nbd7 with at least equality. White currently has more space, but that will change when Black plays one of his pawn breaks  (...e5 or ...c5)  . It's worth mentioning that Black is probably going to choose the ...c5-break because the e5-break requires some preparation. After Black plays ...c5, he can further improve his position with ...Qc7, ...Rac8, ...Bc6, ...Qb7, and maybe ...Ne4. Black should meet a4 with ...a6 to avoid opening the a-file  (a5 can be met with ...b5)  . }
