[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1...Nf6 and 1...f5"]
[Black "1...Nf6 2.Nf3 e6 (move order for Nimzo and QID players)"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3
{ 2.Bf4  d5  Black can commit to ...d5 because White commited to not playing a queen's gambit, avoiding a transposition that Nimzo Indian and Queen's Indian players probably want to avoid. }
2... e6
{ Many players play the Nimzo Indian and/or the Queen's Indian defense against 2. c4, so they probably wouldn't be comfortable playing 2... d5 in response to 2. Nf3 because White could transpose into the Queen's Gambit. }
3. Bf4
{ The London. Black isn't able to play all of my previously recommended lines because Black can no longer play ...Bf5  (he played ...e6 before developing his light-squared bishop)  . For that reason, it's worth giving players who play this move order a good way to fight the London. }
3... c5
{ Counterattacking the center without yet committing the ...d5. Black can choose to play ...d5 soon, but in the meantime, he threatens to obtain a central pawn majority with ...cxd4 and has the option to pressure White's b2-pawn with ...Qb6.  Black can also play   3...b6  which aims for a Hedgehog structure.  4.e3  Bb7  5.Nbd2  Be7  6.h3  O-O  7.Bd3  c5  8.c3  cxd4  9.exd4  d6  In this structure, White has more space but Black has excellent piece harmony and can later try to open the center with ...e5  (or ...d5/...b5 if White plays c4)  . Here is a game where Magnus Carlsen played Black in this position to show how Black can play in this middlegame.  10.O-O  Nbd7  11.Re1  Qc7  12.a4  a6  13.Bh2  Rfe8  14.Qb3  Bf8  15.Re2  Bc6  16.c4  Qb7  17.Rae1  d5  18.cxd5  Bxd5  White's center has been neutralized and now White has a bad version of the isolated queen pawn as his pieces are not well placed to fight for a kingside initiative.  19.Bc4  Rac8  20.Bxd5  Qxd5  21.Qxd5  Nxd5  White does not have any compensation for his d4-pawn being isolated and Black went on to win the endgame.  22.Ne4  Rc6  23.Ne5  Nxe5  24.dxe5  White no longer has an isolated pawn, but his bishop is passive, Black has the d5-outpost, and dominates the open c-file.  24...Rec8  25.Bg3  Bb4  26.Rd1  Rc1  27.Rxc1  Rxc1+  28.Kh2  h6  29.f3  Ra1  30.Rc2  Kh7  31.Bf2  Rxa4  32.Nd6  Kg6  33.Rc4  f5  34.Rc6  Bd2  35.g3  b5  36.Nb7  Ra2  37.Rxe6+  Kh7  38.Bd4  Be3  39.Bxe3  Rxb2+  40.Kg1  Nxe3  41.Rxa6  Rg2+  42.Kh1  Rxg3  43.f4  Rxh3+  44.Kg1  Nd5  45.Nd6  Nxf4  46.Nxf5  Rh5  47.Nd4  Rxe5  48.Rb6  Ne2+  49.Nxe2  Rxe2  50.Rxb5  Re6  Gata Kamsky vs. Magnus Carlsen, 0-1, Moscow Tal Memorial Blitz, 2008 }
4. e3 { 4.c3  Nc6  5.e3  d5  6.Nbd2 } 4... Nc6
{ 4...Qb6  is also playable if Black plans to meet  5.Nbd2  with  5...Qxb2  or   5...d5 }
5. c3
{ The main move.   5.Nbd2  is more accurate than 5. c3, preparing for ...Qb6. If Black now plays ...Qb6, White can play Nc4 !, winning a tempo against Black's queen and defending the b2-pawn.  5...d5  Transposing into a line that I did not recommend. Specifically, 1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Bf4 c5 4. e3 Nc6 5. Nbd2 ! e6. I recommended 5... Bf5 instead of 5... e6, but that isn't possible here because Black played ...e6 on move 2. However, Black can get active play here as well.   5...Qb6 ?  6.Nc4   5...b6  The Hedgehog approach is also playable. For example,  6.c3  Bb7  7.Bd3  Be7  8.h3  O-O  9.O-O  d6  with a Hedgehog like position. This is a somewhat thematic pawn structure, Black will often play ...Re8, ...Qc7-b8, ...Rad1, ...Bf8, and wait for the right time to open the center with ...cxd4 and/or ...e5.   9...d5  is also playable but not in the spirit of ...b6 and ...Bb7 in my opinion because it blocks the bishop.  6.c3  This is a standard London where Black has already commited to playing ...e6, preventing my ...Bf5 recommendation. Black should look for other ways to play actively, ideally deviating from mainline theory, as White is likely to be more familiar with the mainline.  6...Nh5  Black targets White's bishop pair. White is unable to do the same because hasn't played ...Bf5.   6...cxd4 !?  An interesting way of preparing ...Nh5, preventing White from playing dxc5.  7.exd4  Nh5  8.Be3   8.Bg5  f6  9.Be3  Bd6  is similar, the addition of ...f6 is useful for Black provided that he is well developed because Black might play ...e5  (though it might not matter if Black chooses to later play ...f5 and go for a Stonewall structure)  .  8...Bd6  9.Ne5  g6  I'm not sure what the theoretical status of this line is, Black probably isn't objectively equalizing here, but 6... cxd4 is an interesting way to play the ...Nh5 lines without allowing dxc5. The disadvantage of this approach, which is quite serious, is that ...cxd4 gave the e3-square for White's dark-squared bishop, allowing White to escape when Black threatened the bishop pair with ...Nh5. Since I want to win the bishop pair, I prefer the 5... Nh5 line over the 5... cxd5 6. exd4 Nh5 line.  7.Bg5  Otherwise Black would win the bishop pair.  7...Qb6  Black counterattacks the b2-pawn and plans to win the bishop pair with ...h6, ...g5, and ...Nxg3. This is the critical branching point.  8.Rb1  White defends his b2-pawn.   8.Ne5  with a discovered attack on the h5-knight.   8.Qb3  h6  Black resumes his plan to win the bishop pair.  9.Bh4  g5  10.Bg3  Nxg3  11.hxg3  Bg7  Black has a small advantage due to his bishop pair and space advantage.  8...Nf6  White still has to respond to Black's ...Qxb2 threat.  9.Rb1   9.Nxc6  bxc6  helps Black support his center. Black can challenge White's center at any moment with ...cxd4 followed by ...c5 and can develop his light-squared bishop with ...Ba6. Black is also likely to prevent Bxf6 with ...Nd7  (or ...Be7)  and can finish his development with ...Bd6 and ...O-O. Bxf6 is not currently threatening because Black would have the bishop pair, a space advantage, and a lead in development.  9...Nxe5  10.dxe5  Nd7  Black has at least equality due to his central space advantage and White's weak e5-pawn.   8.dxc5  Bxc5  is fine for Black, but  9.b4  is probably best met with  9...Bf8  instead of ...Be7 so that b5 can be met with ...Ne7. Black likely has at least equality here due to his central pawn majority and piece activity. Black will likely target White's bishop pair  (...h6, ...g5, ...Nxg3)  , possibly restrain White's queenside pawn majority   ...a6  , likely meet e4 with ...Qc7  (so Be3 doesn't come with tempo)  and has reasonable chances in this dynamic position.  8...h6  Black targets White's bishop pair.  9.Bh4  g5  10.Ne5  White fights for the initiative with a discovered attack on the h5-knight.   10.Bg3  Nxg3  11.hxg3  Bg7  Black has a small advantage due to his space advantage and bishop pair.  also playable is   11...g4 !?  12.Ne5  Nxe5  13.dxe5  h5  where Black is also better.   10.dxc5  only helps Black develop with  10...Bxc5  10...Nxe5   10...cxd4  11.exd4  Nxe5  transposes to 10... Nxe5.   10...Ng7  is passive.  11.Bg3  Black has inferior piece activity and kingside weaknesses without the bishop pair to show for it.  11.dxe5   11.Qxh5  cxd4  12.exd4  Ng6  13.Bg3  e5 !  White will win the e5-pawn, but Black has the initiative and can follow up with ...Bf5 and ...Bg7. This position is likely playable for both sides but I would rather be Black.  11...Ng7  12.Bg3  Nf5  Black will play ...Nxg3 with a slightly better position due to his bishop pair. }
5... Nh5 { 5...d5  is also playable.  6.Nbd2  Nh5 } 6. Bg5
{ 6.Bg3  Nxg3  7.hxg3  d5  Black has a slightly better position due to his bishop pair. }
6... Qb6 { Black threatens to win the b2-pawn. } 7. Qb3
{ The mainline, by far. White assumes that ...Qxb2 was a threat.   7.Qc2  White defends his b2-pawn.  7...h6  8.Bh4  g5  9.Bg3  Nxg3  10.hxg3  Bg7  11.Nbd2  d5  Black is at least equal  (probably slightly better due to his bishop pair and space advantage)  . Black will rapidly develop and can castle either direction.  Probably strongest is the rare   7.Nbd2 !  but Black is not worse and choose between 3 equalizers  (according to Stockfish 10)  :  7...h6  preparing ...g5 followed by ...Nxg3.  Black can also equalize with   7...d5  which gains space and prevents Nc4.  The third equalizer is   7...Qxb2  which grabs a pawn but increases White's lead in development  (Black will lose time retreating his queen)  . 7... Qxb2 is probably sound for Black but I want to fight for the initiative ! So for the materialists, feel free to grab that pawn and try to win the endgame, and for the others, ...Qb6 was a useful developing move that can bluff the opponent into making a concession  (even if you don't intend to play ...Qxb2, which is a sound option after Nbd2)  . }
7... h6 { Black prepares ...g5 and ...Nxg3, winning the bishop pair. } 8. Bh4
{ 8.Qxb6  This exchange generally helps Black because the doubled pawns aren't isolated and Black obtains the a-file.  8...axb6  9.Bh4  g5  10.Bg3  Nxg3  11.hxg3  Bg7  Black is slightly better due to his bishop pair and control over the open a-file. Black will gians space in the center with ...d5 next. }
8... g5 9. Bg3 Nxg3 10. hxg3 Bg7
{ Black is slightly better due to his bishop pair. Black will play ...d5  (gaining central space)  , rapidly develop, and castle either direction. }
