[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1...Nf6 and 1...f5"]
[Black "Black vs. London (1...f5 move order)"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 f5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Bf4
{ While the London is playable here, it is not as strong against the Dutch. The reason for this is that one of Black's main Dutch plans is ...d6 and ...e5 and Bf4 makes this plan stronger because Bf4 is a target. This is comparable to the ...e5 break in the King's Indian Defense, but it is even more effective in the Dutch because the pawn duo f5 and e5 is stronger than a lone e5-pawn. It's hard to know what to recommend here because some Dutch players play the Leningrad  (...g6 lines)  and some play the Classical  (...e6 lines)  , but the Stonewall isn't the best approach in the London because Bf4 would control the weak e5-square. Black's most thematic plan is to develop rapidly and play for the ...e5 break  (...e6, ...Be7, ...0-0, ...d6, ...Qe8, ...Nc6, and possibly ...Bd8 with ...e5)  . Black can also target White's f4-bishop with ...Nh5 and/or ...h6 with ...g5. }
3... e6
{ I recommend the Classical variation, though the Leningrad is also playable. Black doesn't need to memorize any deeper, just the plan. This is similar to standard Classical Dutch lines where Black has a target on f4, increasing the effectiveness of the ...e5 break and giving him other attacking options  (...Nh5, ...h6 and ...g5)  . }
*

